	<div class="a-column " id="a-col">
	<div id="content" class="hfeed">
	<article class="post-622283 post type-post status-publish hentry category-retailleisure category-technology category-telecommunications tag-accel-partners tag-amazon-com-inc tag-bahl-kunal tag-bharatiya-janata-party tag-delivery-services tag-e-commerce tag-ebay-inc tag-flipkart-com tag-foreign-investments tag-india tag-modi-narendra tag-shopping-and-retail tag-snapdeal-com per-bahl-kunal per-modi-narendra des-delivery-services des-e-commerce des-foreign-investments des-shopping-and-retail org-accel-partners org-amazoncom-inc org-bharatiya-janata-party org-ebay-inc org-flipkart-com org-snapdeal-com geo-india news_keywords-accel-partners news_keywords-bharatiya-janata-party news_keywords-delivery-services news_keywords-e-commerce-2 news_keywords-flipkart-2 news_keywords-foreign-investment news_keywords-india news_keywords-kunal-bahl news_keywords-narendra-modi news_keywords-retail news_keywords-snapdeal" id="post-622283">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/by-industry/technology/">Technology</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">The New Bazaar: In India, Online Stores Catch On With Buyers</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Max Bearak			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-07-30T01:41:25+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 29, 2014 9:41 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 29, 2014 9:41 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/29/the-new-bazaar-online-shopping-catches-on-in-india-with-buyers-and-global-investors/" data-title="The New Bazaar: In India, Online Stores Catch On With Buyers" data-description="E-commerce in India is attracting buyers in a society where Internet access is increasing, and international investors are starting to take note.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/ECOMMERCE1/ECOMMERCE1-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/ECOMMERCE1/ECOMMERCE1-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/ECOMMERCE1/ECOMMERCE1-articleInline.jpg" id="100000003027670" width="190" height="296" alt="A billboard in New Delhi advertises Snapdeal, an online marketplace in India with $1 billion in sales."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="296"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A billboard in New Delhi advertises Snapdeal, an online marketplace in India with $1 billion in sales.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Graham Crouch for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At first, Kunal Bahl and his high school buddy Rohit Bansal had modest ambitions for their online shopping site, Snapdeal.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Their previous venture â a physical coupon booklet into which they had sunk their combined savings â flopped in just months. And online retailing was still a largely unproven endeavor in 2010, particularly in India, a country where most people donât have bank accounts, let alone credit cards to make purchases on the Internet. When an angel investor offered $200,000 as seed money, they took only half and aimed for just 100 transactions a day.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Snapdeal is now on track to handle more than $1 billion in sales this year for over 30,000 merchants across more than 500 categories of goods and services.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe sell a sari every 12 seconds,â Mr. Bahl said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The rise of Indian e-commerce â which has started to gain traction only in recent years â has captured the attention of international investors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This year, Snapdeal has raised $233 million, with about half coming from the American Internet company <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=EBAY&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about eBay Inc">eBay</a>. Mr. Bahl said Snapdeal was considering an initial public offering in a year or two.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At least half a dozen other leading Indian shopping sites have announced major fund-raising deals in recent months. On Tuesday, Flipkart, Indiaâs largest e-commerce company, said that it had raised $1 billion from investors, including American firms like Tiger Global and Accel Partners. The amount represents the largest ever for an Indian Internet company, and globally, it matches <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=FB&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Facebook, Inc.">Facebook</a>âs fund-raising round in February 2011 and ranks only second to <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/06/uber-raises-new-funds-at-17-billion-valuation/">Uberâs $1.2 billion bonanza</a> this June, according to <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=TRI&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Thomson Reuters Corporation">Thomson Reuters</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âE-commerce in India is poised to take advantage of larger shifts in society,â said Vani Kola, now the managing director of Kalaari Capital and formerly of NEA-IndoUS Ventures, Indian-based venture capital firms that both have invested in Snapdeal. âThe whole industry has begun swiftly growing and evolving.â</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/Ecommercejp1/Ecommercejp1-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/Ecommercejp1/Ecommercejp1-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/Ecommercejp1/Ecommercejp1-blog480.jpg" id="100000003027988" width="480" height="320" alt="Internet access has rapidly expanded, mostly through mobile devices, and Indians are now shifting many daily activities online."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Internet access has rapidly expanded, mostly through mobile devices, and Indians are now shifting many daily activities online.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Graham Crouch for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The investment surge reflects the changing landscape in India. Internet access has rapidly expanded, mostly through mobile devices, and Indians are now increasingly shifting daily activity online, like reading the newspaper, doing bank transactions and buying goods and services, from shoes to refrigerators (with installation included).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Billboards, text messages and emails bombard people every day with news of deep online-only discounts and special offers. E-commerce is growing at a compound annual rate of 34 percent, according to the Internet and Mobile Association of India, an industry trade group.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But online shopping remains a largely untapped market. While estimates of the total worth of Indiaâs online retail industry vary greatly, most analysts figure that it accounts for less than 1 percent of the countryâs $500 billion retail market, which is still mostly cash-driven.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Comparatively, Chinaâs e-commerce sales are expected to top $180 billion this year, accounting for roughly 9 percent of the countryâs retail spending, according to iResearch Consulting, which specializes in Chinaâs Internet industry. The countryâs largest online retailer, Alibaba, is <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/07/17/alibaba-said-to-plan-i-p-o-for-september/" title="NY Times article.">expected to go public in the coming months</a> with an estimated value of more than $200 billion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThereâs tremendous headroom still,â Mr. Bahl said. âI think 20 years from now, 20 percent of retail will be online.â</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/ECOMMERCE2/ECOMMERCE2-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/ECOMMERCE2/ECOMMERCE2-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/ECOMMERCE2/ECOMMERCE2-blog480-v2.jpg" id="100000003027672" width="480" height="320" alt="One challenge facing Indiaâs online retailers: Many shoppers still prefer buying from vendors they know in neighborhood shops."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">One challenge facing Indiaâs online retailers: Many shoppers still prefer buying from vendors they know in neighborhood shops.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Graham Crouch for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet particularities to Indiaâs shopping culture have impeded the industryâs growth.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By and large, India remains a bastion of the âkirana,â or neighborhood general store, as well as the roving hawkers, whose nasal cries carry the names of their wares through narrow lanes and up to the top floors of apartment buildings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Most people tend to shop from sellers they know personally and live near, running grains of rice through their fingers and smelling the different varieties to determine their quality before, perhaps, moving to the next shop where they might closely inspect the stitch count of a new batch of shirts sold by the local ready-made clothes dealer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">These entrenched habits, combined with the newness of the Internet and credit cards, have led to a trust gap between online retailers and their customers. To bridge it, the biggest names in e-commerce, including Snapdeal and Flipkart, allow customers to pay cash upon delivery for their purchases and let consumers return items at the very last second, even when the delivery person arrives at their door.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To address the widespread perception that the stateâs postal service is unreliable, e-commerce players like Snapdeal, Flipkart and Jabong have developed their own delivery logistics companies. Snapdeal and others have built fulfillment centers and hired delivery workers to help ensure packages arrive in a timely fashion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The logistic network, in part, has helped Snapdeal court small business owners to its marketplace.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/Ecommercejp2/Ecommercejp2-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/Ecommercejp2/Ecommercejp2-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/30/business/Ecommercejp2/Ecommercejp2-blog480.jpg" id="100000003027989" width="480" height="320" alt="Kunal Bahl, a founder of Snapdeal, which has raised $233 million from investors this year."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Kunal Bahl, a founder of Snapdeal, which has raised $233 million from investors this year.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Graham Crouch for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIn the early days,â Mr. Bahl said, âwe were calling every family and friend who we knew was running a small business or wanting to start one, and for whom nationwide distribution would be a godsend. It was quite hard to convince them, given many of them hadnât ever used the Internet themselves.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Momentum is now on the industryâs side. Mr. Bahl said that the company barely needed to recruit merchants any more, with 80 percent requesting to join Snapdeal. âVirality amongst small business owners is very acute,â Mr. Bahl said. âIf one sees success, then word spreads really, really fast.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Once merchants join the site, Snapdeal works with them to develop their listings and bolster sales. When Rakesh Sareen, 29, started selling his line of traditional womenâs clothing made of locally sourced materials, Snapdeal, as part of its services, promoted the introduction and covered the cost of a photo shoot and online catalog.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThey send out targeted newsletters, which promote our products, and their fashion category manager advises us on trends as well as updates on how certain products of mine are selling,â said Mr. Sareen, who had just returned from a trip to the villages where he buys woven fabric.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Looming large over the industry is last yearâs entrance in India of <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=AMZN&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Amazon.com Inc">Amazon</a>. Huge American online retailers like Amazon and eBay own marketplace platforms here, which, like Snapdeal and Flipkart, connect merchants with consumers. But the countryâs regulations prevent Amazon and other overseas players from selling directly to consumers from their own inventory as they do elsewhere. Currently, foreign investment in multibrand retail is limited to 51 percent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There are hints that the system may be changing, at least in the online space.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The current government, led by the Bharatiya Janata Party, is perceived as backing small business owners who fear that opening retailing to foreign behemoths will put them out of business. But <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/narendra_modi/index.html?inline=nyt-per" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Narendra Modi.">Narendra Modi</a>, Indiaâs new prime minister, recently urged the industry to embrace change at a widely televised rally during his election campaign. âThere is no need to fear global challenges,â said Mr. Modi, adding, âthis is the age of online marketing, so accept modern science and make use of it.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Amazon in particular stands to benefit from any change to the existing rules. âCustomer loyalty isnât so strong yet, so itâs conceivable that Amazon would either look to buy big names here, or their expansion might just kill some of the smaller horizontals altogether,â said Nikhil Pahwa, the founder and editor of <a href="//Medianama.com" class="tickerized" title="The site.">Medianama.com</a>, which analyzes Indiaâs digital economy. On Monday, Amazon announced that it would open five new fulfillment centers across India to bring its nationwide total to seven.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In a recent email, a spokeswoman for Amazon in India affirmed that the company was in âcontinual dialogueâ with the government and that it strongly supports âopening up this sectorâ to foreign direct investment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Bahl of Snapdeal seems unfazed. âIt wouldnât affect our marketplace,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Within the next year, he thinks Snapdealâs network of sellers will reach 100,000, and the company plans to double its number of fulfillment centers as well as engineering employees. As for the prospect of competition from Amazon, he thinks that small businesses will congregate on marketplace platforms like Snapdealâs so as to collaboratively compete against the giants.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWeâre the ones who are going to help small businesses compete against Amazon,â Mr. Bahl said. âWe are that platform.â</p>
